#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:36(para)
msgid "Before we delve into the configurations, we briefly discuss the ciphers' configuration element and its format. A more exhaustive treatment on available ciphers and the OpenSSL cipher list format can be found at: <link href=\"https://www.openssl.org/docs/apps/ciphers.html\">ciphers</link>."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:40(para)
msgid "or"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:44(para)
msgid "Cipher string options are separated by \":\", while \"!\" provides negation of the immediately following element. Element order indicates preference unless overridden by qualifiers such as HIGH. Let us take a closer look at the elements in the above sample strings."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:47(code)
msgid "kEECDH:kEDH"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:49(para)
msgid "Ephemeral Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (abbreviated as EECDH and ECDHE)."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:50(para)
msgid "Ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (abbreviated either as EDH or DHE) uses prime field groups."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:51(para)
msgid "Both approaches provide <link href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forward_secrecy\">Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS)</link>."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:52(para)
msgid "Ephemeral Elliptic Curves require the server to be configured with a named curve, and provide better security than prime field groups and at lower computational cost. However, prime field groups are more widely implemented, and thus typically both are included in list."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:56(code)
msgid "kRSA"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_ssl-proxies-and-http-services.xml:58(para)
msgid "Cipher suites using the <link href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_%28cryptosystem%29\">RSA</link> exchange, authentication or either respectively."
