#: ./security-guide/section_database-access-control.xml:9(para)
msgid "Each of the core OpenStack services (Compute, Identity, Networking, Block Storage) store state and configuration information in databases. In this chapter, we discuss how databases are used currently in OpenStack. We also explore security concerns, and the security ramifications of database back end choices."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_database-access-control.xml:11(title)
msgid "OpenStack database access model"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_database-access-control.xml:12(para)
msgid "All of the services within an OpenStack project access a single database. There are presently no reference policies for creating table or row based access restrictions to the database."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_database-access-control.xml:13(para)
msgid "There are no general provisions for granular control of database operations in OpenStack. Access and privileges are granted simply based on whether a node has access to the database or not. In this scenario, nodes with access to the database may have full privileges to DROP, INSERT, or UPDATE functions."
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_database-access-control.xml:15(title)
msgid "Granular access control"
msgstr ""

#: ./security-guide/section_database-access-control.xml:16(para)
msgid "By default, each of the OpenStack services and their processes access the database using a shared set of credentials. This makes auditing database operations and revoking access privileges from a service and its processes to the database particularly difficult."
